ares boot attempt — task 20.4b / 20.4c evidence
================================================
STATUS 2026-07-23 (supersedes the earlier "ares SIGSEGV" and "NULL WAD" notes)

1. RESOLVED — ares does not crash.
   The original "SIGSEGV before any output" finding was purely a missing X
   display. With xorg-server-xvfb installed, ares starts normally:

       $ xvfb-run -a ares --system "Nintendo 64" --no-file-prompt n64-doom.z64
       OpenGL Version: 4.6 (Core Profile) Mesa 26.1.5-arch3.1, GLSL: 4.60
       OpenGL: Failed to load librashader: shaders will be disabled
       (runs to the timeout; exit 124 = still running, not a crash)

   The librashader line is cosmetic — an optional shader library.

2. RESOLVED — the ROM now embeds an IWAD.
   `make` appends doom.wad at N64_WAD_OFFSET (2 MiB) with n64tool and compiles
   the cartridge address and length into the shim, which registers it as
   "doomu.wad" — one of the names IdentifyVersion() probes (d_main.c:592-630).
   The build asserts the WAD actually landed rather than trusting the tool:

       built n64-doom.z64 with ../../wads/lib/doom.wad at offset 2097152
       WAD magic present in ROM
       ROM size: 14516224 bytes

   The WAD is read IN PLACE from cartridge space (KSEG1, uncached) because it
   cannot fit in RDRAM: 12,408,292 B of WAD against 4 MB (8 MB with an
   Expansion Pak) minus the ~990 KB the engine already holds. Build a
   footprint-only ROM with `make N64_WAD=`.

3. CURRENT BLOCKER — ares emits no ISViewer output for ANY ROM.

   Established by controlled experiment rather than inference. Three ROMs, all
   with the same result (runs to timeout, exit 124, only the two OpenGL lines):

     a. webdoom n64-doom.z64 with the WAD embedded          -> no output
     b. a minimal libdragon ROM whose entire body is
              debug_init(DEBUG_FEATURE_LOG_EMU);
              for (int i=0;i<5;i++) debugf("CONTROL ROM ALIVE %d\n", i);
        built with the same strip + n64tool pipeline        -> no output
     c. libdragon's own examples/ctest, built by libdragon's OFFICIAL pipeline
        (n64elfcompress + n64sym + n64tool + stock IPL3, after installing the
        missing tools into $N64_INST)                       -> no output

   (b) rules out the webdoom port — a ROM that does nothing but print is
   equally silent. (c) rules out our hand-rolled packaging — libdragon's own
   toolchain and IPL3 fare no better. The silence is therefore a property of
   this ares build's ISViewer→stdout path, and tells us nothing about whether
   webdoom boots.

   Reading the ares source, output *should* appear: the channel is allocated
   for any ROM under ~63.9 MB (n64/cartridge/cartridge.cpp:50,
   `rom.size <= 0x03ff0000`; ours is 14.5 MB), the tracer is built with
   setTerminal(true) (cartridge.cpp:52-54), notify() gates on
   `file() || terminal()` (node/debugger/tracer/tracer.hpp:9), and
   Program::log() calls print(message) for a terminal tracer
   (desktop-ui/program/platform.cpp:58-60).

   Why that path yields nothing is unresolved. Note libdragon's isviewer_init()
   probes by writing a magic value and reading it back (src/debug.c:95), so a
   failed probe disables output silently at the ROM end — consistent with what
   we observe, but not yet proven to be the cause.

NEXT STEPS for the 20.4c gate, cheapest first
 - Try a released ares build instead of this from-source master, to rule out a
   regression or a build-option difference.
 - Enable the debugger explicitly (`--setting Boot/Debugger=true`) and see
   whether tracer nodes behave differently once the debugger UI is realised.
 - Failing both, verify through a different channel: ares's DebugServer
   (Developer/DebugServerEnabled, a GDB stub) to confirm the CPU is executing
   and inspect the PC, or capture the framebuffer and assert on rendered output
   instead of UART text.

REPRODUCTION
    source ~/toolchains/env.sh
    cd tools/n64 && make all
    make boot-log ARES=$HOME/toolchains/bin/ares ARES_TIMEOUT=25

Pass ARES explicitly, or put ~/toolchains/bin on PATH: xvfb-run does not
inherit a PATH set only inside the make invocation. Raw capture from each run
goes to ares-boot-raw.log (gitignored); this file is curated evidence.
